  "prompt": "What's the weightage given to 10th, 12th and graduation marks in IIM's selection process?",
  "response": "The selection process for the **Indian Institutes of Management (IIMs)** is holistic and considers multiple criteria. The weightage given to **10th, 12th, and graduation marks** varies across IIMs, but here\u2019s a general overview of how they are typically considered:\n\n### 1. **Academic Performance (10th, 12th, Graduation)**\n   - **10th Marks**: Usually given a weightage of **10%** or less in the selection process. It is considered a baseline indicator of academic consistency.\n   - **12th Marks**: Typically given a weightage of **10-15%**. It reflects the candidate's performance at a higher academic level.\n   - **Graduation Marks**: Often given a weightage of **15-20%**. This is considered more significant as it is the most recent academic qualification.\n\n   Note: Some IIMs may normalize scores across different boards or universities to ensure fairness.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **CAT Score**\n   - The CAT (Common Admission Test) score carries the highest weightage, usually **30-40%** of the total selection criteria.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Work Experience**\n   - Work experience is often given a weightage of **5-10%**. Quality and relevance of the experience matter more than duration.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Diversity Factors**\n   - **Gender Diversity**: Some IIMs give additional points to female candidates.\n   - **Academic and Professional Diversity**: Weightage is given to candidates from non-engineering backgrounds or those with unique work experience.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Personal Interview (PI) and Written Ability Test (WAT)**\n   - After the shortlisting stage, the **PI and WAT** typically carry a combined weightage of **30-40%**. These stages assess communication skills, personality, and analytical thinking.\n\n---\n\n### Example of Weightage at Top IIMs:\n**IIM Ahmedabad**:\n   - CAT: 40%\n   - 10th Marks: 10%\n   - 12th Marks: 10%\n   - Graduation Marks: 20%\n   - PI-WAT: 20%\n\n**IIM Bangalore**:\n   - CAT: 40%\n   - 10th Marks: 5%\n   - 12th Marks: 15%\n   - Graduation Marks: 20%\n   - PI-WAT: 20%\n\n---\n\n### Key Takeaway:\nWhile **CAT score** is the most critical factor, academic performance (10th, 12th, graduation) plays a significant role in shortlisting and final selection. Consistency across these stages is highly valued. Always check the specific weightage for each IIM, as it may vary slightly.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
